   <span class="Entry">Events</span>
   <h2 class="Entry"><div class="title_link"><a href="http://www.thecoolhunter.co.uk/article/detail/1581/level-green">Level Green</a></div></h2>
   <span class="Small">July 18 2009<br /></span>
   <div class="Content">
   <p><img alt="" src="http://www.thecoolhunter.com.au/images/jmayer.jpg" /></p>
<p>A new permanent exhibition, LEVEL GREEN, dealing with the complex topics of car manufacturing, sustainability and the use of global resources, opened last month at the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.autostadt.de/portal/site/www/template.">Autostadt</a> (Car city in German), near the Volkswagen factory in Wolfsburgh, Germany.<br />
<br />
The architectural firm of <a target="_blank" href="http://www.jmayerh.de/home.htm">J. Mayer H. </a>of Berlin and interactive an digital media specialists,<a target="_blank" href="http://www.artcom.de/"> Art+Com</a> Berlin, developed the concept for the 1,000 m2 interactive exhibition. The themes of the exhibition &mdash; Personal use, Sustainability at Volkswagen, The three aspects of sustainability, Mobility of the future, Sustainability and the economy, Effects of climate change &mdash; wind their way among an organically-shaped, sustainably built web of green structures.</p>
<p><img width="680" height="452" alt="" src="http://www.thecoolhunter.com.au/images/jmayer1.jpg" /><br />
<br />
Established in 1994, the vast is a seven-pavilion Autostadt visitor attraction area has ultra-modern pavilions for Volkswagen, Bentley, &Scaron;koda, Lamborghini, Audi and SEAT, and draws about 2 million visitors annually.<em><strong> - Tuija Seipell</strong></em></p> 
   </div>
